And the said William then and there appeared in person, and having viewed and understood for himself the aforesaid copies, letterS, and evi- dences he affirmed and recognised that all such letters and clauses as are alleged to have been written in the name of the aforesaid John Lydeyard had come to his hands, and that he believing them to have been written and sent by the aforesaid John had written the aforesaid responsory letters and clauses with his own hand, as has been stated above. Moreover he admitted that about St.. Katherine’s Day last he went with the aforesaid Robert Poleyn to the aforesaid Tower, and that no one was at the time in the room where the aforesaid records were kept, except themselves, two only, just as the same Robert has already explained, and that the said William then with his fingernail rased the number XL contained in the said inquisition at the time of his visit, and with fresh ink wrote again the same number, blotting it, in order that in this point especially it might appear (a matter) for suspicion. Hereupon he was asked what number was first found there in the aforesaid inquisition in the aforesaid place of the rasure at the time of his visit. He said only the number XL, nothing greater or smaller. He was asked at whose instigation he went to the aforesaid Tower to make such rasure.
